<subSubSection id="679F657CFFAB5F69FF0CCB32A385959D" pageId="11" pageNumber="278" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="2F3A36F7FFAB5F69FF0CCB32A6BE9545" blockId="11.[151,1436,1189,1826]" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis id="1DF1EAE5FFAB5F69FF0CCB32A3329625" bold="true" box="[199,314,1297,1322]" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Body length 2.0– 
<quantity id="E87D9B12FFAB5F69FDEACB31A0779626" box="[545,639,1298,1322]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="11" pageNumber="278" unit="mm" value="2.1">2.1 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis id="1DF1EAE5FFAB5F69FD5ACB32A0EB9625" bold="true" box="[657,739,1297,1322]" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">Colour</emphasis>
. Body integument black; vestiture of elytra consisting of recumbent, slightly overlapping brown scales, slightly longer than wide, concealing integument, and white scales usually forming a pale oblique band between humeri and apical third of elytral suture. 
<emphasis id="1DF1EAE5FFAB5F69FBA3CB7AA6A0967D" bold="true" box="[1128,1192,1369,1394]" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">Head</emphasis>
. Rostrum moderately downcurved in lateral view, as long as head capsule + prothorax. 
<emphasis id="1DF1EAE5FFAB5F69FC4FCB5EA1F69699" bold="true" box="[900,1022,1405,1430]" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">Prothorax</emphasis>
. Slightly wider than long (w/l ratio: 1.15), sides moderately rounded in basal 2/3, constricted in apical 1/3, with spots of whitish scales near humeri and at base near scutellum. 
<emphasis id="1DF1EAE5FFAB5F69FE61CBE6A3FE96D1" bold="true" box="[426,502,1477,1502]" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">Elytra</emphasis>
. Subparallel in basal two-thirds (w/l ratio: 0.65), rounded toward apex in apical third. 
<emphasis id="1DF1EAE5FFAB5F69FF12CBCAA319950D" bold="true" box="[217,273,1513,1538]" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">Legs</emphasis>
. Covered with white and brown scales; femora moderately clavate, armed with small but distinct ventral tooth, tibiae straight; claws unequal in length, at least for fore tarsi. 
<emphasis id="1DF1EAE5FFAB5F69FC7BC82EA6169529" bold="true" box="[944,1054,1549,1574]" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">Genitalia</emphasis>
. Penis elongate (w/l ratio: 0.30), sides straight, subparallel, converging near apex; curvature moderate in lateral view (
<figureCitation id="B7BE2A72FFAB5F69FB9BC812A6A29545" box="[1104,1194,1585,1610]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1825,1847]" captionTargetBox="[196,1389,189,1792]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[165,1416,189,1815]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Penis of Smicronyx from tropical Africa, in dorsal (left) and lateral (right) view. A. Smicronyx bisignatus Hoffmann, holotype ♂. B. S. remaudierei Hoffmann, holotype ♂. C. S. adjamati, sp. n., holotype ♂. D. S. crassithorax sp. n., paratype ♀. E. S. zambianus sp. n. holotype ♂. F. S. syriacus Faust, specimen from Israel (♂). G. S. gossypii Marshall, holotype ♂. H. S. albosquamosus Wollaston, specimen from Israel (♂). I. S. pauperculus Wollaston, specimen from Tanzania (♂). J. S. rufus sp. n., holotype ♂. K. S. zonatus sp. n., holotype ♂. L. S. kenyanus sp. n., holotype ♂. M. S. namibicus sp. n., holotype ♂. N. S. kiboanus Voss, paratype ♂. O. S. guineanus Voss, specimen from Senegal (♂). P. S. buchnerae sp. n., holotype ♂. Scale bars (A to N): 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2607098/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">Fig. 5H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2F3A36F7FFAB5F69FF0CC876A385959D" blockId="11.[151,1436,1189,1826]" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis id="1DF1EAE5FFAB5F69FF0CC876A3589561" bold="true" box="[199,336,1621,1646]" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">Life history</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="E8854D74FFAB5F69FE96C875A02E9561" authorityName="Wollaston" authorityYear="1854" box="[349,550,1621,1646]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Smicronyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albosquamosus">
<emphasis id="1DF1EAE5FFAB5F69FE96C875A02E9561" box="[349,550,1621,1646]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">S. albosquamosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found on 
<taxonomicName id="E8854D74FFAB5F69FD7BC875A1049562" box="[688,780,1622,1645]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Cuscuta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="11" pageNumber="278" phylum="Magnoliopsida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1DF1EAE5FFAB5F69FD7BC875A1049562" box="[688,780,1622,1645]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">Cuscuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. in the Mediterranean region. Adults were collected in 
<collectingCountry id="57927667FFAB5F69FF5CC85AA2E4959D" box="[151,236,1657,1682]" name="Zambia" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">Zambia</collectingCountry>
in November.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="679F657CFFAB5F69FF0CC8BEA01595D5" pageId="11" pageNumber="278" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2F3A36F7FFAB5F69FF0CC8BEA01595D5" blockId="11.[151,1436,1189,1826]" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis id="1DF1EAE5FFAB5F69FF0CC8BEA36895B9" bold="true" box="[199,352,1693,1718]" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is widely distributed throughout the Mediterranean basin. It is here reported here for the first time in tropical Africa.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="679F657CFFAB5F69FF0CC8C6A6A2942D" pageId="11" pageNumber="278" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="2F3A36F7FFAB5F69FF0CC8C6A6A2942D" blockId="11.[151,1436,1189,1826]" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis id="1DF1EAE5FFAB5F69FF0CC8C6A34495F1" bold="true" box="[199,332,1765,1790]" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="E8854D74FFAB5F69FE98C8C5A07495F1" authorityName="Wollaston" authorityYear="1854" box="[339,636,1765,1790]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Smicronyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albosquamosus">
<emphasis id="1DF1EAE5FFAB5F69FE98C8C5A07495F1" box="[339,636,1765,1790]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="278">Smicronyx albosquamosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other species of tropical Africa by its claws, which are unequal in length, at least for the fore tarsi (claws equal in length in other species).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
